INSTALLATION INSTRUCTIONS

Linux terminal: $ cat * > "Ubuntu 17.10.zip"
Windows 10 PowerShell: $ cmd /c copy /b * "Ubuntu 17.10.zip"

Unzip "Ubuntu 17.10.zip," and open "Ubuntu 17.10.vmx" in VMware Workstation 15 Player.
If one sees a login prompt, simply restart the virtual machine.

Caveats:
OpenShot 1.4.3 is unstable, so save the project frequently.
The image does not provide root access. If one needs root access, replicate the image (see below).

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
OPTIONAL

To verify the authenticity of "Ubuntu 17.10.zip":
$ gpg --keyserver hkps://keyserver.ubuntu.com:443 --recv-keys 0x4191f431
$ gpg --verify SHA1SUMS.gpg SHA1SUMS (example)

To verify the integrity of "Ubuntu 17.10.zip":
Linux terminal: $ sha1sum "Ubuntu 17.10.zip" (example)
Windows 10 PowerShell: $ Get-FileHash "Ubuntu 17.10.zip" -Algorithm SHA1 (example)

One can ignore ERROR 1 and the message, ``No LADSPA plugins were found!'' 
To address ERROR 1 anyway, either launch OpenShot with Python from the ``openshot'' directory:
$ cd /usr/share/openshot/openshot
$ python -m openshot
...or instruct OpenShot to launch immediately from the ``openshot'' directory, instead of trying /openshot/bin:
$ sudo nano /usr/bin/openshot
Change line 53 to ``from openshot.openshot import main'' (excluding quotation marks)

To address ``ladspa'' anyway, install---for example---the LADSPA SDK: 
$ sudo apt install ladspa-sdk
(One may need to re-launch OpenShot twice, for it to recognize the newly installed plugin.)

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

HOW THE IMAGE WAS CREATED

Downloaded the base operating system:
ubuntu-17.10-desktop-amd64.iso
(source: http://old-releases.ubuntu.com/releases/17.10/)

VMware Workstation 15 Player:
Created a new virtual machine entitled "Ubuntu 17.10" using Easy Install
Memory: 4 GB, Processors: 2, Virtualize Intel VT-x/EPT

Modifications/changes:
+ updated /etc/apt/sources.list with the latest server URL, and updated package lists:
  $ sudo sed -i -re 's/([a-z]{2}\.)?archive.ubuntu.com|security.ubuntu.com/old-releases.ubuntu.com/g' /etc/apt/sources.list
  $ sudo apt update
+ installed OpenShot and GStreamer Libav plug-in:
  $ sudo apt install openshot gstreamer1.0-libav
+ upgraded all packages:
  $ sudo apt upgrade
+ enabled automatic login:
  Settings > Details > Users > Automatic Login: ON
- disabled automatic screen lock:
  Settings > Privacy > Screen Lock > Automatic Screen Lock: OFF
- removed the lock screen button from the status menu:
  $ dconf write /org/gnome/desktop/lockdown/disable-user-switching true
+ set up the project directory:
  (see README)
+ bookmarked the project directory in Nautilus
  Click on, and drag, the ``introduction'' folder to left panel onto ``New bookmark.''
+ created a shortcut to the project directory on the desktop:
  Nautilus > Preferences > Behavior: select ``Show action to create symbolic links''
  Right-click on ``Default Project.osp,'' and select ``Create Link.''
  Click on, and drag, the link to the desktop.
+ added Terminal and OpenShot to Favorites:
  Open each application; in the Dash right-click on the application; and select ``Add to Favorites.''
- streamlined the Dash:
  For each application, in the Dash right-click on the application and select ``Remove from Favorites.''
- selected ``never'' to notify me when a new Ubuntu version is available:
  Software Updater > Settings > Notify me of a new Ubuntu version: Never

Sent "Ubuntu 17.10.vmdk" and "Ubuntu 17.10.vmx" into a compressed folder, "Ubuntu 17.10.zip"